Gerald,<br><br>
Thanks for your insight. Your observation on the bifurcation of the world into &quot;pure&quot; polarity by some who cannot appreciate the real world in between is on the mark. In a way I have sorrow for people such as KT, for the true meaning of life lies in feelings between the extremes. These polarized individuals are missing the reality of experiencing humanity.<br><br>
My burnout was a time for some quiet introspection on where I was and where I am going. In my exploration into what it means for me to be a Vietnam Veteran, to acknowledge that I am a Vietnam Veteran, and what am I to do with all these new found feelings and points of view, is a challenge. The end product of my introspection was a view just to let it all flow. <br><br>
Lately, I find my thoughts turning more to images and feelings of the Wall. In a month it will be my first anniversary of my visit to the Wall. I will visit there again next month. Hanging out with the feelings I experienced from that first encounter was a turning point I shall never forget.<br><br>
I will just keep the faith! 
